@mpkorstanje Yes, came to the same conclusion checking your second scenario with a trivial `CloseablePath` instance caching via:

```java
		var uri = getClass().getResource("/jartest.jar").toURI();
		try (var first = CloseablePath.create(uri)) {
			assertTrue(first.getPath().getFileSystem().isOpen());
			try (var second = CloseablePath.create(uri)) {
				assertSame(first, second);
				assertTrue(first.getPath().getFileSystem().isOpen());
				assertTrue(second.getPath().getFileSystem().isOpen());
			}
			assertTrue(first.getPath().getFileSystem().isOpen()); // this fails as expected!
		}
```

Thanks @marcphilipp, amazingly what you suggested with the `UniqueIdSelector` works. 

I followed your advice and collected unique ids from a discovered test plan. I was not sure which TestIdentifiers were needed so I collected all of them from starting at the root. 

```java
// Initial Request
final LauncherDiscoveryRequest request = LauncherDiscoveryRequestBuilder.request()
                .selectors(
                        selectPackage("com.oscar.samplelib"),
                        selectClass(SampleJavaClass.class)
                ).filters(
                        includeClassNamePatterns(".*SampleJavaClass")
                ).
                build();

// Test plan to do discovery once and get unique ids 
final TestPlan testPlan = launcher.discover(request);

// Collect all unique ids
final List<UniqueIdSelector> selectors = testPlan.getRoots()
            .stream()
            .flatMap(testIdentifier ->
                    Stream.concat(testPlan.getDescendants(testIdentifier)
                            .stream(), Stream.of(testIdentifier))
                            .map(x -> DiscoverySelectors.selectUniqueId(x.getUniqueId()))
            ).collect(Collectors.toList());

// Permanent request (for all subsequent calls)  
launcherDiscoveryRequest = LauncherDiscoveryRequestBuilder.request()
                .selectors(selectors)
                .build();
```
After I followed the build steps again and reused the discovery request upon calling `Launcher.execute` the warnings no longer appear. 

My only question is about the safety of the approach? I understand doing test discovery like this is not exactly the standard approach outlined in the JUnit documentation. 

Doing it the way you suggested has also netted a > 10% performance improvement in my limited performance testing done so far. It still remains to be seen how a single discovery request will actually fit into my application. Thank you again for showing me this :)
